<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-736-443  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 736 443.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 18 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Desktop drives U.S. telecom market, says IRD. (InternationalResources Development)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Resources Development (Reports).andO;Topic:     Future of ComputingTelecommunicationsTrendsReports.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DESKTOP DRIVES U.S.andP;  TELECOM MARKET, SAYS IRD 12/18/90 NEW CANAAN,CONNECTICUT, U.S.A., 1990 DEC 18 (NB) -- Software trends driven by PC usersare replacing the telephone hardware realities of the telecommunicationsmarket, according to market researchers at International ResourcesDevelopment.andP;  And the trend is likely to accelerate.andM;According to a new report by Elizabeth Hafner of IRD, &quot;Telecommunicationsfirms are realizing that their futures are determined more by what happens toWindows than by ISD&quot; as PCs linked by local area networks (LANs) become themainstream of office automation.andP;  The resulting communication between LANsare creating new markets in things like bridges and routers, a trend whichwill accelerate as fiber allows LANs to handle images and full- motion videoover the next few years.andP;  Tomorrow's LANs will handle voice calls, too, thereport adds.andM;Still, this is a huge market growing even bigger.andP;  Total sales of telecomequipment and services were $200 billion this year, and the total will riseto $320 billion by the end of the decade, despite increasing efficiency.andO;Fiber, fax, and cellular will provide the fastest growth, according toHafner.andM;The major trends driving the market include the combination of data and voiceonto the same lines, new services like audiotex which can be accessed easilyover touchtone phones, the replacement of thermal-paper fax machines bycomputers, the growth of cellular services and emerging digital cellularstandards, fiber optics, and continuing competition in phone equipmentmarkets.andP;  Data communications should grow faster than voice, the reportconcludes, but the oil shock will have little long-term impact.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19901218/Press Contact: Elizabeth Hafner, IRD,203-966-2525)</TEXT></DOC>